eural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pregnenolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994699358940125, "span": {"begin": 584, "end": 596}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9607662558555603, "span": {"begin": 631, "end": 638}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11-KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985907077789307, "span": {"begin": 649, "end": 654}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013739"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994078874588013, "span": {"begin": 675, "end": 687}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1584"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CYP11&beta;1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9785890579223633, "span": {"begin": 716, "end": 728}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3290"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HSD11&", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9767470955848694, "span": {"begin": 733, "end": 739}}], "text": "The cholesterol molecule is the precursor for all steroid hormone synthesis. Cholesterol is obtained from de novo synthesis within cells or uptake of extracellular cholesterol (Eacker et al., 2008), however the dependence on either source varies by species (Klinefelter et al., 2014). Cholesterol is then transported into the inner mitochondrial membrane via the steroidogenic acute regulatory protein (StAR). Cholesterol is then converted to pregnenolone via the enzyme cytochrome P450 side-chain cleavage (cyp11a1). This is the rate-limiting step of steroidogenesis (Arukwe, 2008). Pregnenolone is then used to produce all other steroid hormones. 11-KT is synthesized from testosterone primarily using the enzymes CYP11&beta;1 and HSD11&beta;2 (Yazawa et al., 2008).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:25:59 +0000 2026"}